Analysis of Attrition of Employees for Company Dataset

By Peter Apazidis and Mohammed Kabir

This project is based on a dataset from Kaggle representing different attributes about the relationship between employees and a certain company (the company name was not given). The task given by the person who supplied the dataset is to find out why many of the employees at their company are leaving. Supposedly, there are a few attributes that might be a major part of the reason for the growing amount of departures from the company. Link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/patelprashant/employee-attrition

Tidying the Data

We do not need the "Over18", "StandardHours", and "EmployeeCount" columns because all of the entries in these rows are the same values. That matters because if all entries are the same, whether an employee leaves or stays at the company wont be affected at all by a variable that never changes regardless. The "DailyRate" column is dropped because it can be derived from the "HourlyRate" attribute, so its data is redundant. "EmployeeNumber" contains only unique entries that simply identify employees, which is not relevant to the problem of finding out the reason behind attrition.

In [ ]:
df.drop(columns=["Over18","StandardHours","EmployeeCount", "DailyRate", "EmployeeNumber"], inplace=True)
In [ ]:
df.rename(columns = {"Attrition": "Label"}, inplace=True)

We want to encode attribues whose entries consist of words. This is because it will enable the machine learning model to train on categorical attributes. Most of the encodings for these attributes had to be made arbitrarily since there is no correct way to encode them. However, for binary attributes we encoded them as 0s and 1s, where 0s represented the negation of something while 1s represented the positives.

Exploratory Data Analysis and Visualizations

Now that we have tidied up the dataset and encoded whatever attributes we needed, it is time to analyze the data and find trends. A good start to doing this is creating a heatmap of correlations between each of the attributes against each other. This way, we get a very broad overview of the relationships between different attributes, which can be used to quickly find certain trends.

The heatmap below is based on Pearson's coefficient, where the range of values for each entry is between -100% and 100% inclusive, indicating how negatively or positively correlated attributes are respectively. A value of 0% would indicate no correlation.

If there are any attributes that have strong negative or positive correlations, then it could indicate redundancy in the dataset. There happens to be such a type of correlation between "MonthlyIncome" and "JobLevel", which makes sense since the more presegious jobs typically come with a higher paying salary. One of these attributes will have to be deleted because highly correlated attributes tend to introduce bias into machine learning models.

df_enc.drop(columns=["JobLevel"], inplace=True)

Having looked at all the different attributes of the dataset, it is reasonable to suspect that the increase in attrition would be due to a lack of job satisfaction. It is generally known in the job market that people who leave their jobs often do so because they are not satisfied with them. The pie charts below seems to confirm this belief. As the satisfaction level of employees increases, the ratio of workers that stay to workers that leave decreases. However, this information may not be useful because job satisfaction usually depends on multiiple other variables, such as income, work environment, job type, etc. We are going to look at the ratio of workers that stay to workers that leave in terms of other attributes to find out what may be causing dissatisfaction.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,20))
job_sat_li = df_enc['JobSatisfaction'].unique()
job_sat_li.sort()
sat_labels = ['very dissatisfied', 'somewhat dissatisfied', 'somewhat satisfied', 'satisfied']
for i, level in enumerate(job_sat_li):
  attrition_vals = df_enc[df_enc['JobSatisfaction'] == level]['Label']
  attrition_cnts_dic = attrition_vals.value_counts().to_dict()
  # print(attrition_vals.value_counts().to_dict())
  plt.subplot(1, 4, i+1)
  plt.title(sat_labels[i])
  plt.pie([attrition_cnts_dic[0], attrition_cnts_dic[1]], labels=['stayed','left'], autopct='%0.0f%%')

According to the correlation heatmap, there is a relatively significant correlation between "TotalWorkingYears" (the number of years an employee worked at a company) and attrition. From the pie charts below it can be seen that this correlation holds true, but more so at the extreme data points. That is, there is a small difference between the attrition of employees that have worked between 5-19 years, but there is a huge difference between those who had worked 0-4 years and those who worked more than 19 years.

The ranges of the bins for the pie charts above were set somewhat arbitrarily. Within each range there could be a subset of data that skews the result of the pie graph. For example, in the 5-9 range of TotalWorkingYears, those who worked 5-6 years may have a much higher attrition rate than those who worked 7-9 years. Thus, we want to play around with adjusting the ranges to see if we can get more specific information about employees who worked a certain range of years. The 0-4 range seems to be yielding some interesting data, so we will start by dividing that range into smaller ranges.

After dividing the 0-4 range into smaller bins, we find that we were right in guessing that our data was skewed. Almost exactly half of all employees that worked less than 1 year left the company, while only about 20% left of those who worked 4-5 years. Using this information, we can narrow our analysis of attrition down to finding how employees who worked less than 1 year correlates with other attributes in the dataset.

Looking back at the correlation heatmap, it can be seen that the attributes "TotalWorkingYears" and "MonthlyIncome" have a relatively high correlation between each other. To better visualize the relationship between these two attributes we created a scatter plot with a best fit line. The strong positive slope of the line indicates that as the TotalWorkingYears of the employees increases, so does their pay. Given that employees of companies are generally driven by the amount of money they are paid, it is a reasonable hypothesis that employees who just started in this company are unhappy with the amount of income they receive.

Another attribute that had a high correlation with "TotalWorkingYears" was "JobRole". "JobRole" has been encoded from words to numbers in order for our model to process the data for it. The below graph again only looks at the "TotalWorkingYears" divided into 3 bins: employees with less than or equal to 1 year of work, employees with 2-3 years of work, and employees with 4-5 years of work. A possible reason as to why a decent chunk of Laboratory Technicians stay may be because as they work longer, they get paid more, a trend that we have seen before in the correlation matrix.

def get_label(role_num):
  for role in categories_encoded["JobRole"]:
    if categories_encoded["JobRole"][role] == role_num:
      return role

According to the correlation heatmap, "OverTime" (employees who have worked overtime) is the most correlated attribute with attrition. As shown by the pie charts, a significantly greater amount of employees left the company when they had worked overtime, versus those who didn't. More specifically, it was a difference of 21%. In our learning models we are likely to see OverTime as the most influential factor of attrition at the company because of this. It is exepected that other attributes who had high correlations with attrition in the correlation matrix will be significant contributors as well.

Let's Train Some Models

In the analysis, hypothesis testing, and ML phase we are going to see if we can learn a way to predict attrition. Since the prediction is just going to consist of whether the employee leaves the company or not, this is clearly a classificatin problem. We want to train some model to classify whether a given employee is likely to leave the company or stay based on the data we have about the employee.

For the previously mentioned reasons, we will drop the following columns from the dataframe.

The classication models we will use only work with numerical data. So we have to handle the non-numerical columns in some way. Since we cannot remove all of them we have a way to convert/encode them in a way that does not introduce bias into our data. Department, Education Field, Gender, JobRole, MaritalStatus, and OverTime are all categorical data while BusinessTravel is ordinal data.

Handling ordinal data is easy. We can just assign a unique number to each value, in a way that represents their natural order.

The Attrition attribute is going to be our y-label so we will also assign 1 to the 'Yes' value and 0 to the 'No' value.

In [ ]:
# We represent 'encoding' as a dictionary where the keys are the attribute names 
# and the values are dictionaries where the keys are the non-numerical values and the values are the numerical assignments.
category_encoding = {
    "Attrition": {"No":0, "Yes": 1}, #y-label
    "BusinessTravel": {"Non-Travel": 0, "Travel_Rarely":1, "Travel_Frequently":2} #Ordinal Data
}

Now, we need to encode our sample's non-numerical categorical data in a way that does not introduce bias in the form of a false notion of order. There are a few libraries for this such as LabelEncoder, BinaryEncoder, OneHotEncoder, etc. However, we will just use the pandas get_dummies() method to get us what is effectively a binary encoding. It essentially goes through each non-numerical column and unwinds the categories within the column into category-column per category. It then assigns a 1 under the category-column that corresponds to the category that belonged to the employee originally and 0 else where. OneHotEncoder is recommended for ML that goes into production because get_dummies() does not encode unseed data in production. However, this tutorial is not going into production.

We need to partition our data into a training sample and a testing sample along with the corresponding labels. For our small dataset, we have found the sweet spot to be around a 75-25 split. Our dataset also suffers from a disproportionate ratio of 'No' to 'Yes' labels. This is why we use the stratify argument in the train_test_split() method. We use the stratify argument to ensure that relative class frequency is preserved across the train-test split.

First up: DecisionTreeClassifier¶

A decision tree is a visualizable, interpretable, supervised classification model. Starting at the root and at each node it tries to split on a feature that is least ‘polarizing’ and gives the most information in a way that most of the observations in each side of a split fit in a unique target classification. It stops splitting when most or almost all of the observations at a node fit with a unique target classification. It does this while also attempting to minimize loss between predicted values and actual values. It is easy for a decision tree to over fit the training data, but methods such as depth-bounding, pruning, and setting a minimum number of observation at a leaf level may help reduce overfitting.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
In [ ]:
# Obtain a decision tree classifier
dtCLF = DecisionTreeClassifier()
# Fit the classifer on the training sample

# Test the classifier on the testing sample

# Generate performance report
report_dtCLF = metrics.classification_report(ypredictions_dtCLF, y_test)

# Print results
print(f'Tree Depth: {dtCLF.get_depth()}')
print(f'Accuracy score: {accuracy_score(y_test, ypredictions_dtCLF)}')

Our decision tree classifier scored poorly. It seems to have poor precision and recall, especially when predicting when an employee could leave. Let's see what happens when we switch from the gini criterion to entropy. A max depth of 15 seems like the tree could grow overly complex so we will limit the maximum depth to 7. We will also limit the minimum observations or samples a leaf can have to 50.

In [ ]:
# Obtain a decision tree classifier with custom parameters
entropy_dtCLF = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy', max_depth=7, min_samples_leaf=50)

# Test the classifier on the testing sample

print(f'Accuracy score: {accuracy_score(y_test, ypredictions_entropy_dtCLF)}')

Our decision tree improved with some parameter tuning however the both the precision and recall were low especially when the model classified an employee is likely to leave. To be fair this dataset is just s snapshot and that employee could have left after the snapshot. However we want to see if we can find a model that can improve on at least one of these metrics.

Precision ratio: (The number of employees the model correctly classifies as likely to leave) TO (the total number of employees the model claims are likely to leave).

Recall ratio: (The number of employees the model correctly classifies as likely to leave) TO (the total number of employees that actually leave).

It would be ideal to improve both precision and recall drastically, but usually we can tune for one at a time. We did improve our recall and thus our overall score. However, it seems like the model is quick to classify an employee is likely to leave. The upside is that of those employees the model classifies as likely to leave, a majority of them do leave. Let's see if a different model can provide improved predictions.

Next up: RandomForestClassifier¶

A random forest is a large ensemble of decision trees that vote their respective classifications on a particular observation. The trees are built with various samples (with replacement) of the data in a way that the trees are not correlated and bias is reduced. The trees will all classify the same observation then vote their result, and the majority vote in the forest wins. The hope is that forest of trees outperform any individual tree.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
In [ ]:
# Obtain an instance of a random forest classifier
rfCLF = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=500, criterion='entropy')

# Fit the classifier on the training sample
rfCLF.fit(X_train, y_train['Attrition'])

# Test the classifier on the testing sample
ypredictions_rfCLF = rfCLF.predict(X_test)

# Generate performance report
report_rfCLF = metrics.classification_report(ypredictions_rfCLF, y_test)

# Print results
print(f'Accuracy score: {accuracy_score(y_test, ypredictions_rfCLF)}')
print(f'Classification report: \n{report_rfCLF}')

Accuracy score: 0.8586956521739131

Recall performance has improved with the random forest classifier while precision performance remains low. The overall score has only a slight improvement. We did not bound the depth of the decision trees within the ensemble because having an ensemble in the first place would help cancel out the bias from overfitting an individual tree does on its sample. However we kept the criterion the same since entropy can have a slightly higher accuracy despite being slower than gini. Let's see the feature importances as calculated by the random forest.

However, MonthlyIncome is the most important here, and OverTime is further down the list.

Bonus round: LogisticRegresssion¶

According to sklearn LogisticRegression is also a classifier model despite the regression name. Is is a maximum-entropy classifier that can fit binary classification. We will use the lbfgs solver because it is good for small datasets and it is robust.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Obtain an instance of Logistic regressor (classifier)
logregCLF = LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs', max_iter=10000)

# Train the classifier on the trainig sample
logregCLF.fit(X=X_train, y=y_train['Attrition'])

# Test the model on the testing sample
yprediction_logregCLF = logregCLF.predict(X_test)

# Generate performance report
report_logregCLF = metrics.classification_report(yprediction_logregCLF, y_test)

# Print results
print(f'Accuracy score: {accuracy_score(y_test, yprediction_logregCLF)}')
print(f'Classification report: \n{report_logregCLF}')

LogisticRegression predicts when an employee is not likely to leave with high precision and recall. It also improves its precision on employees that classifies as likely to leave while maintaining a relatively similar recall performance.

Conclusion

In predicting the attrition of employees, there is no one attribute whose values can tell us whether an employee is going to leave the company or not. It turns out that there are multiple attributes that are needed to predict attrition at least somewhat accurately. This is reflected by the charts presented in the exploratory data analysis section of this project, where multiple correlation relationships were needed to explain the possible trends that affected the attrition rate. This result was expected because jobs are very important to people, and so it would make sense that multiple aspects of a company would drive people to leave, not just one or two.

From what relationships we could identify as being the most significant in determining the attrition rate, we found that overtime, monthly income, and total years worked at the company had the most effect on attrition. More specifically, people who had less total years working at the company, especially within 1 year, whose monthly income was low, and who worked overtime were the most likely to leave the company.

For our machine learning model we were not able to break the 90% accuracy barrier with our three models: DecisionTree, RandomForest, and LogisticRegression. The most accurate model we used is the LogisticRegression with 89% accuracy score followed by RandomForest and DecisionTreeClassifer that both hovered around 86%. One metric that all three models performed poorly on is precision on positive classifications. It seems that the models more often incorrectly attempted to classify employees as likely to leave. One reason this maybe is because the proportion of the positive class is way smaller than the proportion of the negative class. It understandable then that since there are way fewer positive observations than there are negative observations that the models could yield many false positives. One possible remedy to this is to train the models on much larger dataset, however we do not have access to a larger dataset from this company.
